definitions.definition: From one side or end of (something) to the other .

subdefinitions.definition: So as to enter (something), pass within or across , and then leave .
examples: I drove through Lausanne on my way from Geneva to Zurich.
The bullet went right through his leg.

subdefinitions.definition: So as to progress within (something) or towards the end or limit of (something).
examples: The virus broke out in the capital city and is now spreading quickly through the country.
I'm working through this box set of 'Downton Abbey'.

subdefinitions.definition: From one side of (an opening) to the other.
examples: Go straight ahead and through that door.
Look through the window.

subdefinitions.definition: To or beyond the other side of (an obstacle); past .
examples: I hope to start in the autumn, but I've got to get through the interview first.
The finance bill did not get through Congress.
We're through the worst part.
The going will be easier once we're through the bog.
You can't see through a brick wall!

subdefinitions.definition: Indicating that something has been consumed or used up .
examples: Have you got through all those chocolates already?!
The company went through its £100m startup investment in six months.
subdefinitions.label_groups: in phrases such as 'go through', 'get through' etc.

subdefinitions.definition: Along the course of; used in expressions of progress towards the end of something .
examples: We're halfway through the year.
He worked through the night.
I never want to sit through another meeting like that again.
The hot water enters through this pipe.

subdefinitions.definition: By way of (an intermediary, agent, medium, etc.).
examples: I met her through a friend of mine.
This matter was dealt with through our London office.
I received this anonymous letter through the post.

definitions.definition: Throughout or across the extent of.
examples: There are errors all through this report.
Work the eggs and sugar through the mixture.
We slogged through the mud for hours before turning back and giving up.
The arrow flew through the air.
I spent all day wading through paperwork.

definitions.definition: To (or up to ) and including, with all intermediate values; to... inclusive; until the end of.
examples: from 1945 through 1991;  the numbers 1 through 9; your membership is active through March 15, 2013
This team believes in winning through intimidation.
He's got to where he is today through sheer hard work and determination.

definitions.definition: In consequence of; as a result of.
examples: The project failed through lack of investment.

main_definition: From one side or end of (something) to the other .
secondary_definitions: Throughout or across the extent of.
( Canada , US ) To (or up to ) and including, with all intermediate values; to... inclusive; until the end of.
In consequence of; as a result of.
